{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513560","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513560"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:11:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:11:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12159"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12159","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12159"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.65,0.06,0.08,0.13,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4689"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53668"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4689","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4689"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12159"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39133"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"439"},{"type":"tags","id":"8850"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7250"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7285"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53668","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53668"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man presents to his general practice with a lump on his eyelid which has been mildly irritating but mostly painless. It has been present for three days. The image of the eyelid is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the best initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Apply heat and massage daily","Surgical incision","Refer to ophthalmology urgently","Topical antibiotics, eg chloramphenicol ointment","Watch and wait"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA chalazion is a painless lump caused by inflammation of the meibomian gland of the eyelid. Chalazion can be painful and red if it becomes infected. Unless infected, it will usually self-resolve without the need for antibiotics. \u003Cstrong\u003EApplication of heat and daily massage \u003C/strong\u003Ecan aid in recovery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgical incision \u003C/strong\u003Eand \u003Cstrong\u003Ereferral to ophthalmology\u003C/strong\u003E may be needed if the chalazion unresolved is or if large and symptomatic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical antibiotics eye drops\u003C/strong\u003E are useful if the chalazion is associated with inflammatory conditions such as blepharitis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Chalazion, also known as a meibomian cyst, is a self-limiting inflammatory lesion of the eyelid and usually self-resolves."],"references":["Boyd K, Pagan-Duran B. Chalazia and Stye. American Academy of Ophthalmology. EyeSmart\u00ae Eye health. https://www.aao.org/eye-health/diseases/chalazia-stye. Accessed March 07, 2019","RACGP (https://www.racgp.org.au/download/Documents/AFP/2009/May/200905gilchrist.pdf)","Kanski JJ. Eyelids. In: Clinical Ophthalmology: A Systematic Approach. 4th edition. Boston ; Oxford : Butterworth-Heinemann1999: 9-12.","Jordan GA, Beier K. Chalazion. [Updated 2022 Jul 7]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK499889/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39133"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12159"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21051"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21051","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21051"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.e